Data Imputation

Here, for the variables BPXSY1 and BPXDI1, I first divided the participants into two groups based on mortality statuses (0 or 1), then I perform imputation of these two variables separately by filling the NA values with the median value of that group. This is because participants who died or did not die may have a difference in some key vital signs (such as blood pressure), so performing imputation after separating the data will help to represent the distribution of the true population. My strategy will also apply to the rest of the continuous variables with NA values in this data frame, including LBXRDW (Red cell distribution width (%)), BPXML1 (Maximum inflation levels), BMXBMI (Body Mass Index), and BMXWAIST (Waist circumference).

For the rest variables with NA values (both categorical and binary), I will impute the variables based on a majority rule of responses from the participants. This applies to variables HSD010, VIQ200, and BPXPULS. Still, my imputation will be carried out after separating participants based on mortality statuses.

for (var in continuous_vars) {
  alive_group[[var]] <- as.numeric(as.character(alive_group[[var]]))
  deceased_group[[var]] <- as.numeric(as.character(deceased_group[[var]]))
}

# Use median value to impute missing NA's among continuous variables
impute_median <- function(data, variables) {
  for (var in variables) {
    data[[var]][is.na(data[[var]])] <- median(data[[var]], na.rm = TRUE)
  }
  return(data)
}

alive_group <- impute_median(alive_group, continuous_vars)
deceased_group <- impute_median(deceased_group, continuous_vars)

# Use majority value to impute missing NA's among categorical variables
impute_majority_rule <- function(data, variables) {
  for (var in variables) {
    majority_value <- names(sort(table(data[[var]]), decreasing = TRUE))[1]
    data[[var]][is.na(data[[var]])] <- majority_value
  }
  return(data)
}

alive_group <- impute_majority_rule(alive_group, categorical_vars)
deceased_group <- impute_majority_rule(deceased_group, categorical_vars)

Data Scaling

Next, we consider the necessity for performing one-hot encoding for categorical variables and min-max scaling for continuous variables. I argue that one-hot encoding is necessary in the way that some categorical variables such as WHQ040 and BPQ010 have multiple levels with some different ordinal relationships. E.g., for BPQ010, the levels are determined based on increasing time intervals (short time period > long time period), while for WHQ040, the levels are determined based on whether or not people tend to weight more, less, or stay the same. The order of variable levels differs between different categorical variables, and thats why I think one-hot encode all the categorical variables in the data set is useful.

For min-max scaling (or \(z\) standardization as an alternative strategy), I think it is necessary because the continuous variables have different units (\(mm\ Hg,\ kg/m^2\), etc.) and they have different kinds of distribution, with some dense around the median, some others have relative wide ranges.

library(gbm)
## Loaded gbm 2.2.2
## This version of gbm is no longer under development. Consider transitioning to gbm3, https://github.com/gbm-developers/gbm3
train_set$mortstat <- as.numeric(train_set$mortstat)
test_set$mortstat <- as.numeric(test_set$mortstat)
shrinkage_values <- c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.2, 0.3)
results <- list()

for (i in shrinkage_values) {
  gbm_model <- gbm(
    mortstat ~ .,               
    data = train_set,            
    distribution = "bernoulli",  
    n.trees = 100,               
    interaction.depth = 3,       
    shrinkage = i,      
    n.minobsinnode = 10,        
    cv.folds = 10,               
    verbose = FALSE             
  )
  
  best_trees <- gbm.perf(gbm_model, method = "cv", plot.it = FALSE)
  
  results[[as.character(i)]] <- list(
    model = gbm_model,
    best_trees = best_trees,
    cv_error = gbm_model$cv.error[best_trees]
  )
}

alive_group_raw <- imputed_data %>% filter(mortstat == 0) %>% dplyr::select(-SEQN)
deceased_group_raw <- imputed_data %>% filter(mortstat == 1) %>% dplyr::select(-SEQN)

set.seed(123456)

alive_train_ind_raw <- sample(seq_len(nrow(alive_group_raw)), size = floor(0.8 * nrow(alive_group_raw)))
alive_train_raw <- alive_group_raw[alive_train_ind_raw, ]
alive_test_raw <- alive_group_raw[-alive_train_ind_raw, ]

deceased_train_ind_raw <- sample(seq_len(nrow(deceased_group_raw)), size = floor(0.8 * nrow(deceased_group_raw)))
deceased_train_raw <- deceased_group_raw[deceased_train_ind_raw, ]
deceased_test_raw <- deceased_group_raw[-deceased_train_ind_raw, ]

train_set <- bind_rows(alive_train_raw, deceased_train_raw)
test_set <- bind_rows(alive_test_raw, deceased_test_raw)

train_set$mortstat <- as.factor(train_set$mortstat)
test_set$mortstat <- as.factor(test_set$mortstat)


x_train <- train_set %>% dplyr::select(-mortstat)
y_train <- train_set$mortstat

x_test <- test_set %>% dplyr::select(-mortstat)
y_test <- test_set$mortstat 


svm_linear_tune <- tune(svm, mortstat ~ ., data = train_set, kernel = "linear", ranges = list(cost = c(0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10)))

summary(svm_linear_tune)

                     data = train_set,               # Your training dataset
                     kernel = "radial",              # Radial kernel
